LAMBDA EXPRESSIONS (C++11 onwards) – INTERVIEW NOTES
=========================================

1. What is a Lambda Expression?
------------------------------
  
- A lambda is an anonymous (unnamed) function.
- Introduced in C++11.
- Used to write inline, short functions without defining a separate function.
- Very commonly used with STL algorithms.

Now:

Lambda object → stored inside std::function
std::function hides the actual type.

Think of it like this:
Lambda object
      │
      ▼
+-------------------+
| std::function<>   |
|  (wrapper)        |
+-------------------+

A lambda expression creates an object of a unique, compiler-generated closure type. It is not a std::function. 
std::function is a separate type-erased wrapper that can hold a lambda, function pointer, or any other callable.****

