3. CAPTURE LIST []

Capture list tells the lambda which variables from the surrounding scope it can access.

---------------------------------------------------------
A) Capture Nothing

[]

Example:

auto f = []()
{
    cout << "Hello";
};

• Cannot access local variables. ****
error as its local 
int main()
{
    int a=20;
    auto ptr = [](){a++;return a;}; //compiler error a not captured 
    cout<<ptr(); 
    return 0;
}

to fix issue capture by ref 
int main()
{
    int a=20;
    auto ptr = [&](){a++;return a;}; //compiler error a not captured 
    cout<<ptr(); 
    return 0;
}
• Can access global variables.CVVVVVVVIMP
int a=20;
auto ptr = [](){a++;return a;};
int main()
{
    cout<<ptr();  //prints 21 here 
    return 0;
}

[] is the capture list. An empty capture list means the lambda does not capture any local variables 
from the surrounding scope. Therefore, it cannot access local variables unless they are passed as parameters.
However, it can still access global variables, static variables, and other entities that don't require capture.

---------------------------------------------------------
B) Capture Everything By Value

[=]

Example:

int x = 10;
int y = 20;

auto f = [=]()
{
    cout << x << " " << y;
};

Characteristics

• Copies all used local variables.
• Original variables remain unchanged.
• Variables become read-only unless mutable is used.

---------------------------------------------------------
C) Capture Everything By Reference

[&]

Example:

int x = 10;

auto f = [&]()
{
    x++;
};

Characteristics

• No copy created.
• Modifies original variable.

---------------------------------------------------------
D) Capture One Variable By Value

[x]

Example:

int x = 10;

auto f = [x]()
{
    cout << x;
};

---------------------------------------------------------
E) Capture One Variable By Reference

[&x]

Example:

int x = 10;

auto f = [&x]()
{
    x++;
};

---------------------------------------------------------
F) Mixed Capture

[x,&y]

Example:

int x = 10;
int y = 20;

auto f = [x,&y]()
{
    cout << x;
    y++;
};

x is copied

y is referenced

---------------------------------------------------------
G) Capture Everything By Value Except One

[=,&x]

Everything copied

Only x referenced

---------------------------------------------------------
H) Capture Everything By Reference Except One

[&,x]

Everything referenced

Only x copied

---------------------------------------------------------
I) Capture this Pointer

class Test
{
    int x = 10;

public:

    void fun()
    {
        auto f = [this]()
        {
            cout << x;
        };
    }
};

Allows access to member variables and member functions.

