7. constexpr :If possible, evaluate this expression/function at compile time instead of runtime.

Without constexpr
int square(int x)
{
    return x * x;
}

int main()
{
    int a = square(5);
}

Here:

Compiler generates machine code.
When the program runs, square(5) is called.
Multiplication happens during execution.

This is runtime evaluation.

With constexpr
constexpr int square(int x)
{
    return x * x;
}

int main()
{
    constexpr int a = square(5);
}

Since 5 is known during compilation,

the compiler computes

5 * 5 = 25

while compiling.

The executable already contains

constexpr int a = 25;

No multiplication occurs at runtime.

*********

Normal lambda

auto square = [](int x)
{
    return x * x;
};

Runs at runtime.

Compile-time lambda

constexpr auto square = [](int x)
{
    return x * x;
};

Now

constexpr int ans = square(5);

Compiler computes

25

When does constexpr actually work?

Only when all inputs are known at compile time.

