8. noexcept :noexcept means:

"This function promises that it will not throw any exceptions.

Specifies lambda won't throw exceptions.

Example

auto f = []() noexcept
{
    cout << "Hello";
};

Why use noexcept?
1. Better Optimization

Since the compiler knows exceptions won't occur, it can generate more efficient code.

****
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main()
{
    int a = 10;
    int b = 20;

    auto squareSum = [a, &b](int x) mutable constexpr noexcept -> int
    {
        a++;        // OK because of mutable (modifies the lambda's copy)
        b++;        // OK because b is captured by reference

        return a + b + x;
    };

    cout << squareSum(5) << endl;   // 36
    cout << b << endl;              // 21
}




****

2. Required by STL*****VVVVVIMPP

Many STL containers prefer moving objects only if the move constructor is noexcept.

Example:

class A
{
public:
    A(A&&) noexcept
    {

    }
};

When a std::vector grows, it may move its elements.
If the move constructor is noexcept, the vector will move objects instead of copying them, which is usually faster.********

